RRULE:FREQ=YEARLY
SUMMARY:🌊 Periwinkle Season
DESCRIPTION:Scientific name: Littorina scutulata\nDifficulty: Moderate\nHab
 itat: Rocky intertidal zones above mussel beds\nSeason: Jan\, Feb\, Mar\, 
 Apr\, May\, Jun\, Jul\, Aug\, Sep\, Oct\, Nov\, Dec\nRegions: Sonoma\, Men
 docino\, Marin\, Peninsula\n\nSmall edible shore snails found clinging to 
 rocks above the waterline. Traditional food on the Sonoma and Mendocino co
 asts. Mild flavor\, chewy texture — like small clams.\n\n⚠ Lookalike: 
 No dangerous lookalikes among edible snails at this size.\n\n💡 Harvest 
 tip: Requires CA fishing license. Boil 3–4 minutes. Extract with a pin. 
 Check for biotoxin advisories like mussels.\n\n— Cedar · Northern Calif
 ornia Foraging App
CATEGORIES:COASTAL,MODERATE
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
STATUS:CONFIRMED
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:cedar-season-0273@cedar.norCal
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260401
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260601
RRULE:FREQ=YEARLY
SUMMARY:🌾 Scotch Broom (flowers/shoots) Season
DESCRIPTION:Scientific name: Cytisus scoparius\nDifficulty: Hard/Expert\nHa
 bitat: Roadsides\, open disturbed areas\, coastal scrub\nSeason: Apr\, May
 \nPeak: Mar\, Jun\nRegions: Sonoma\, Mendocino\, Marin\, Santacruz\, Footh
 ills\n\nInvasive broom blanketing Northern California hillsides in spring 
 yellow. Very young unopened flower buds are edible as a caper substitute 
 — the rest of the plant is toxic.\n\n⚠ Lookalike: Similar broom specie
 s vary in edibility. Entire plant is toxic EXCEPT very young flower buds a
 nd shoots. Use extreme caution. Never eat leaves\, seeds\, or mature plant
 .\n\n💡 Harvest tip: CAUTION: Only the very young flower buds before ope
 ning are edible\, pickled like capers. Rest of plant is toxic. Harvesting 
 it is an ecological service — it's highly invasive.\n\n— Cedar · Nort
 hern California Foraging App
CATEGORIES:INVASIVES,HARD
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
STATUS:CONFIRMED
END:VEVENT
