DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260201
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260501
RRULE:FREQ=YEARLY
SUMMARY:🌾 Yellow Starthistle (young rosette) Season
DESCRIPTION:Scientific name: Centaurea solstitialis\nDifficulty: Hard/Exper
 t\nHabitat: Dry roadsides\, overgrazed hillsides\, disturbed fields\nSeaso
 n: Feb\, Mar\, Apr\nPeak: Jan\, May\nRegions: Napa\, Lake\, East\, Foothil
 ls\, Sonoma\n\nThe most invasive weed in California (15+ million acres inf
 ested). Young first-year rosette leaves edible before spines develop — s
 imilar to artichoke in flavor. Harvesting it is a genuine ecological servi
 ce.\n\n⚠ Lookalike: Mature plant has viciously sharp spines — only you
 ng pre-spine rosettes are safe to handle.\n\n💡 Harvest tip: ONLY harves
 t the low flat first-year rosette in winter/early spring before flower sta
 lk emerges. Once spines appear\, do not touch. Young leaves blanched are m
 ild and slightly artichoke-flavored.\n\n— Cedar · Northern California F
 oraging App
CATEGORIES:INVASIVES,HARD
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
STATUS:CONFIRMED
END:VEVENT
