DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20261001
RRULE:FREQ=YEARLY
SUMMARY:🍇 Sierra Currant Season
DESCRIPTION:Scientific name: Ribes nevadense\nDifficulty: Easy\nHabitat: Mo
 ist mountain slopes\, stream banks\, conifer forest\nSeason: Jul\, Aug\, S
 ep\nPeak: Jun\, Oct\nRegions: Tahoe\, Donner\, Foothills\n\nBlue-purple mo
 untain currant common throughout the Tahoe basin. Tart\, juicy berries exc
 ellent for jam\, syrup\, and fresh eating. Clusters of 5–15 berries hang
 ing below branches.\n\n⚠ Lookalike: No dangerous lookalikes — classic 
 currant appearance with smooth berries.\n\n💡 Harvest tip: Found along s
 tream banks and in moist forest in the Tahoe basin at 5\,000–9\,000 ft e
 levation. Peak July–August. Less spiny than gooseberry.\n\n— Cedar · 
 Northern California Foraging App
CATEGORIES:BERRIES,EASY
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
STATUS:CONFIRMED
END:VEVENT
